          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>During gastrulation, epiblast cells migrate through the primitive groove. If a c</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During gastrulation, epiblast cells migrate through the primitive groove. If a cell reaches the deepest layer and replaces the hypoblast, which structures will it eventually form?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Skin epidermis and sensory neurons</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Skin epidermis and sensory neurons derive from ectoderm, the surface layer that remains on top — not the deepest layer formed during gastrulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Gut lining, liver, and lungs</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Cells migrating to the deepest position replace the hypoblast to form endoderm, which lines the gut and gives rise to the liver and lungs.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Heart, kidneys, and skeletal muscles</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>These structures arise from mesoderm, the middle layer. Cells that become mesoderm pass through the streak but stop between ectoderm and endoderm, not at the deepest level.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Dorsal root ganglia and melanocytes</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>These arise from neural crest cells, which emigrate from the neural folds during neurulation — a later process, not part of gastrulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember the spatial rule: cells that migrate deepest through the primitive streak replace the hypoblast to become endoderm — lining the gut, liver, and lungs."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. Endoderm is the deepest germ layer formed during gastrulation and gives rise to the epithelial lining of the gastrointestinal and respiratory tracts."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
