          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A prenatal ultrasound at 20 weeks reveals a foetus with absence of the calvarium</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A prenatal ultrasound at 20 weeks reveals a foetus with absence of the calvarium and cerebral hemispheres. Which developmental failure most likely caused this finding?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Failure of caudal neuropore closure</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Caudal neuropore closure failure (day 27) produces spina bifida — a defect at the lower end of the neural tube, not at the cranial vault.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Persistence of the primitive streak beyond the fourth week</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Primitive streak persistence leads to sacrococcygeal teratoma at the coccyx, not to absence of the cranial vault.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Failure of cranial neuropore closure</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The cranial neuropore normally closes by day 25. Failure leads to anencephaly — absence of the calvarium and cerebral hemispheres — a condition incompatible with life.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Defective migration of neural crest cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Neural crest cell migration defects cause craniofacial anomalies or Hirschsprung disease, not absence of the entire calvarium and cerebral hemispheres.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The cranial neuropore closes by day 25. When it fails, the brain and skull vault cannot develop — this is anencephaly, incompatible with life."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Anencephaly results from cranial neuropore closure failure and is the most severe neural tube defect, readily detectable on routine anomaly scans."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
