          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Somites differentiate into three components — sclerotome, myotome, and dermatome</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Somites differentiate into three components — sclerotome, myotome, and dermatome. Which of the following correctly pairs a component with its derivative?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Dermatome → skeletal muscles of the trunk</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The dermatome forms the dermis of the back and corresponds to the sensory distribution of one spinal nerve. Skeletal muscles arise from the myotome.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Myotome → vertebral bodies and ribs</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The myotome gives rise to skeletal muscles of the trunk, not bony structures. Vertebral bodies and ribs are sclerotome derivatives.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sclerotome → dermis of the back</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The dermis of the back is derived from the dermatome, not the sclerotome. The sclerotome contributes to the axial skeleton.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sclerotome → vertebral bodies, arches, and intervertebral discs</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The sclerotome, the ventromedial portion of the somite, migrates around the notochord to form the vertebral column — including bodies, arches, discs, and ribs.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember the three somite derivatives: Sclerotome → Skeleton (vertebrae, ribs), Myotome → Muscles (trunk), Dermatome → Dermis (back)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The three somite derivatives — sclerotome (vertebrae, ribs), myotome (trunk muscles), dermatome (back dermis) — map directly to bone, muscle, and skin."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
